  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And we have sent with them our brother.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Who this second unnamed brother was is again simply matter of conjecture. Of the names connected with St. Paul at this period, that of Tychicus seems to have the greatest balance of probabilities in its favour. He went up with St. Paul to Jerusalem on this very business (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 20:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the tone in which the Apostle speaks of him in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 6:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Colossians 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", exactly agrees with his language here. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Timothy 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", we have further evidence of his being one of the most trusted of the couriers, or “messengers,” of the Apostolic Church. The name of Clement has, however, I think, some claim to consideration. St. Paul refers to him as an active fellow-worker (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philippians 4:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He was connected with the Philippians. Assuming his identity with Clement of Rome, this gives him a point of contact with the Church of Corinth, to which Clement addressed his Epistle. On the other hand, the distinction drawn in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Corinthians 9:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " between these brethren and the Macedonians may seem to exclude Clement, as it has been thought to exclude Aristarchus and Sopater and Secundus. The word translated “diligent” (“earnest” in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Corinthians 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is used by St. Paul only in this passage. It implies what we might almost call the “business-like” side of the Christian type of character, and is therefore employed with special fitness here.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "8:16-24 The apostle commends the brethren sent to collect their charity, that it might be known who they were, and how safely they might be trusted. It is the duty of all Christians to act prudently; to hinder, as far as we can, all unjust suspicions. It is needful, in the first place, to act uprightly in the sight of God, but things honest in the sight of men should also be attended to. A clear character, as well as a pure conscience, is requisite for usefulness. They brought glory to Christ as instruments, and had obtained honour from Christ to be counted faithful, and employed in his service. The good opinion others have of us, should be an argument with us to do well.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And we have sent with them our brother - Who this was is wholly unknown; and conjecture is useless. Some have supposed that it was Apollos, others Silas, others Timothy. But there are no means of ascertaining who it was; nor is it material. It was some one in whom Paul had entire confidence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Whom we have oftentimes proved diligent - Of whom we have evidence that he has been faithful. It is evident, therefore, that he had been the companion and fellow-laborer of Paul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But now much more diligent ... - Who will now prove himself much more diligent than ever before.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Upon the confidence ... - Margin, \"he hath.\" The margin is doubtless the more correct reading here. The idea is, that this brother had great confidence in the Corinthians that they would give liberally, and that he would, therefore, evince special diligence in the business. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Upon the confidence ... - Margin, \"he hath.\" The margin is doubtless the more correct reading here. The idea is, that this brother had great confidence in the Corinthians that they would give liberally, and that he would, therefore, evince special diligence in the business. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "22. This second brother, Birks supposes to be Trophimus: for a Macedonian is not meant (2Co 9:4) probably the same as was sent before with Titus (2Co 12:18); and therefore sent from Ephesus, and probably an Ephesian: all this is true of Trophimus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "oftentimes … in many things—Join and translate as in the Greek, \"many times in many things.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "upon the great confidence which I have in you—\"through the great confidence WHICH HE HAS towards you\" [Alford]. Bengel better supports English Version, \"We have sent … through the confidence WHICH WE FEEL in regard to your liberality.\"",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "brother",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is uncertainly guessed at, nor is it at all material for us to know whether it were Epenetus, or Apollos, or Sosthenes, or any other; it is sufficient for us to know, that he was a brother, and one of whose diligence and faithfulness the apostle, and the churches where Paul now was, had had experience; and that he was now very ready and forward to be employed in this service, upon the apostle’s recommendation of this church unto him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
